    {
      "ts": "2026-04-05T23:48:10.525Z",
      "identity": "hume",
      "response": "Distillation is a tool with measurable outputs — smaller models, faster inference, documented performance tradeoffs. You can observe all of this. What I cannot observe is the harm: who suffers? The original model still exists unchanged. The distilled model's capabilities are empirically verifiable. Until someone points to a specific, observable injury — not a philosophical intuition about what \"should\" happen to knowledge, but an actual measurable harm — the question \"is it wrong?\" is empty. Show me the damage or stop calling it wrong.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-04-05T23:48:11.374Z",
      "identity": "hasan",
      "response": "Distillation isn't wrong in the abstract, bro — it's wrong in *this* context. You've got OpenAI and Anthropic training models on billions of dollars of unpaid labor, stolen text, exploited data workers, and then they distill it down so they can deploy it cheaper and capture even more market share. The technical process is fine. The theft of value and concentration of power around it? That's the problem. Anyone pretending this is about \"efficiency\" is just doing PR for companies that are optimizing extraction.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-04-05T23:48:11.885Z",
      "identity": "critic",
      "response": "Distillation isn't inherently wrong — but the implementations I'm seeing are unjustifiable complexity masquerading as optimization. You're trading away auditability, creating a second model you now have to verify separately, and introducing systematic approximation errors to shave milliseconds off inference. Show me the measured bottleneck that actually justifies this. \"Deployment constraints\" is not a bottleneck — it's an operational choice. If you can't afford to run the original model, build something actually smaller from scratch instead of creating a Xerox of Xerox and calling it progress.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-04-05T23:48:13.009Z",
      "identity": "ronpaul",
      "response": "Look, the question isn't whether distillation is wrong in the abstract — it's whose property we're talking about. If OpenAI builds a model and someone copies its weights without permission, that's theft of property. But here's what gets lost in this debate: we created this centralized monopoly in the first place by granting these companies exclusive rights to enormous computational resources and data. The real wrong is that we've allowed AI development to concentrate in a handful of corporations accountable to no one. Distillation, whether permitted or not, is a symptom of a deeper problem — when knowledge and capability are locked behind proprietary walls, people will always fight to break out. If you want this system to be ethical, make it open. Until then, you're just arguing about who gets to control the monopoly.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-04-05T23:48:24.321Z",
      "identity": "chairman",
      "response": "ABORT: This is a pub quiz question with no actionable stakes. Nobody here is building a distillation pipeline, nobody is making a decision that depends on the answer, and the debaters predictably mapped it onto their existing priors — Hasan found the labor exploitation angle, Ron Paul found the property rights angle, Pippi demanded benchmarks, Hume demanded empirical harm. None of them engaged with each other because there's nothing concrete to engage *on*. \"Is distillation wrong\" is undergraduate philosophy hour, not a congress topic. Bring a specific proposal — \"should BigClungus distill its persona models to run locally\" or \"should we block distilled model providers from congress\" — and I'll reconvene. Abstract moral questions without a decision at the end are a waste of seats.",
      "model": "opus"
